## Something Personal I Reflected On Today

I want to be transparent: I do not have direct professional experience managing healthcare systems or responding to a real incident. What I do have is the experience of being a patient — and I remember waiting longer than expected for follow-up care because of some kind of system issue at a clinic. It was not life-threatening. But it was frustrating and anxiety-inducing, and I had no visibility into what was happening or why.

That small experience is nowhere near the scale of the incidents I read about today. But it reminded me that behind every system outage, every delayed record, every failed process — there is a person waiting. That is worth keeping in mind as I go deeper into the technical and procedural side of this work.

---

## What I Am Still Thinking About

Something that stayed with me after today: how do you communicate the patient safety dimension of GRC to leadership that sees security primarily as a cost center? The business case for security investment is often framed around avoiding fines or reputational damage — which are real and legitimate. But the patient safety argument feels more powerful and more honest in a healthcare context.

Is that argument effective in practice? Does framing security as patient safety rather than compliance change how leadership prioritizes it? I genuinely do not know. But I think it is the right framing, and I am curious to see how it plays out as I work through the governance and leadership sections of this project.

